# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: indigenous-australians
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The second question of the 1967 Australian referendum of 27 May 1967, called by the Holt government, related to Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Voters were asked whether to give the Commonwealth Parliament the power to make special laws for Indigenous Australians, and whether Indigenous Australians should be included in official population counts for constitutional purposes.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The term "the Aboriginal Race" was used in the question.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Technically the referendum question was a vote on the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginals) 1967 that would amend section 51(xxvi) and repeal section 127.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendments to the Constitution were overwhelmingly endorsed, winning 90.77% of votes cast and having majority support in all six states.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendment became law on 10 August 1967.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1901, the attorney-general, Alfred Deakin, provided a legal opinion on the meaning of section 127 of the Constitution of Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 127 excluded "aboriginal natives" from being counted when reckoning the numbers of the people of the commonwealth or a state.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] His legal advice was that "half-castes" were not "aboriginal natives".
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Prior to 1967, censuses asked a question about Aboriginal race to establish numbers of "half-castes" and "full-bloods".
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] "Full-bloods" were then subtracted from the official population figure in accordance with the legal advice from the attorney-general.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Strong activism by individuals and both Indigenous and non-Indigenous groups greatly aided the success of the 1967 referendum in the years leading up to the vote.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Calls for Aboriginal issues to be dealt with at the federal level began as early as 1910.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From here, the overall plight of Aboriginal Australians became a fundamental political issue.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On 7 April 1965, the Menzies Cabinet decided that it would seek to repeal section 127 of the Constitution at the same time as it sought to amend the nexus provision, but made no firm plans or timetable for such action.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In August 1965, attorney-general Billy Snedden proposed to Cabinet that abolition of section 127 was inappropriate unless section 51(xxvi) was simultaneously amended to remove the words "other than the aboriginal race in any state".
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] He was rebuffed, but gained agreement when he made a similar submission to the Holt Cabinet in 1966.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the meantime, his Liberal colleague Billy Wentworth had introduced a private member's bill proposing *inter alia* to amend section 51(xxvi).
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1964, the Leader of the Opposition, Arthur Calwell, had proposed such a change and pledged that his party, the Australian Labor Party, would back any referendum to that effect.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1967, the Australian Parliament was unanimous in voting for the alteration bill.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Voters were asked to approve, together, changes to two provisions in the Constitution section 51(xxvi) and section 127.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] And the extraordinary clauses that follow (ordinarily referred to as heads of power) list most of the legislative powers of the federal parliament.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendment gave the Commonwealth parliament power to make "special laws" with respect to Aboriginal People living in a state; the parliament already had unfettered power in regard to territories under section 122 of the Constitution.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Constitution required the calculation of "the people" for several purposes in sections 24, 89, 93 and 105.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 89 related to the imposition of uniform customs duties and operated until 1901.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 93 related to uniform custom duties after being imposed by section 89 and operated until 1908.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 105 related to taking over state debts and was superseded by section 105A inserted in the Constitution in 1929 following the 1928 referendum.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Accordingly, in 1967, only section 24 in relation to the House of Representatives had any operational importance to section 127.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 24 "requires the membership of the House of Representatives to be distributed among the States in proportion to the respective numbers of their people".
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The number of people in section 24 is calculated using the latest statistics of the Commonwealth which are derived from the census.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 51(xi) of the Constitution enabled the Parliament to make laws for "census and statistics" and it exercised that power to pass the *Census and Statistics Act 1905*.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] At this time, territorians, while able and required to vote in elections, were not permitted to vote in referendums.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is frequently stated that the 1967 referendum gave Aboriginal people Australian citizenship and that it gave them the right to vote in federal elections; however, this was not the case.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From 1944, Aboriginal people in Western Australia could apply to become citizens of the state, which gave them various rights, including the right to vote.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This citizenship was conditional on adopting "the manner and habits of civilised life" and not associating with Aboriginal people other than their parents, siblings, children, or grandchildren, and could be taken away at any time.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Most Indigenous Australians continued to be denied the right to vote in elections for the Australian Parliament even after 1949.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The *Commonwealth Electoral Act 1962* gave all Aboriginal people the option of enrolling to vote in federal elections.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was not until the *Commonwealth Electoral Amendment Act 1983* that voting became compulsory for Aboriginal people, as it was for other Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Aboriginal people (and all other people) living in the Northern Territory were not allowed to vote in the referendum, which remained the case for both the Northern Territory and the Australian Capital Territory until the Constitutional amendment to section 128 after a referendum in 1977.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is also sometimes mistakenly stated that the 1967 referendum overturned a Flora and Fauna Act.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This is believed to have come from the New South Wales *National Parks and Wildlife Act* 1974, which controlled Aboriginal heritage, land and culture.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The other states had equivalent acts which were managed by various departments, including those relating to agriculture and fishing.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 127 prevented the inclusion of the Indigenous Australians in the official population for constitutional purposes, i.e. their population would not be included in the calculation of the number of seats to assign for each state or in the determination of tax revenue.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The section did not prevent the Bureau of Statistics from counting or collecting other information about Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From 1911 to 1966 the Bureau had collected information about Indigenous Australians, however this was published separately to the general population.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Inclusion in the general population was thus important symbolically, but the change did not directly improve the information available to government.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Ninety percent of voters voted yes, and the overwhelming support gave the Federal Government a clear mandate to implement policies to benefit Aboriginal people.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Many misconceptions have arisen as to the outcomes of the referendum, some as a result of it taking on a symbolic meaning during a period of increasing Aboriginal self-confidence.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was some five years before any real change occurred as a result of the referendum, but federal legislation has since been enacted covering land rights, discriminatory practices, financial assistance, and preservation of cultural heritage.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was the intention of the government and many voters that this new power was to be only used beneficially.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, in the 1998 case of *Kartinyeri v Commonwealth*, the High Court did not find that such a restriction on the power existed, with the court being split 2:2 (2 judges not deciding) as to whether or not the power could be used to the *detriment* of an identified race.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Hindmarsh Island bridge controversy and the Northern Territory Intervention are two circumstances where the post-1967 race power has arguably been used in this way.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The 1967 referendum has acquired a symbolic meaning in relation to a period of rapid social change during the 1960s.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] As a result, it has been credited with initiating political and social change that was the result of other factors.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The real legislative and political impact of the 1967 referendum has been to enable, and thereby compel, the federal government to take action in the area of Aboriginal Affairs.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Federal governments with a broader national and international agenda have attempted to end the discriminatory practices of state governments such as Queensland and to introduce policies that encourage self-determination and financial security for Aboriginal people.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, the effectiveness of these policies has been tempered by an unwillingness of most federal governments to deal with the difficult issues involved in tackling recalcitrant state governments.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It has been argued that Holt, who died not long after the referendum, was setting up a more extensive government response than Gorton enacted.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The benefits of the referendum began to flow to Aboriginal people in 1972.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On 26 January 1972, Aboriginal peoples erected the *Aboriginal Tent Embassy* on the lawns of the Federal Parliament building in Canberra to express their frustration at the lack of progress on land rights and racial discrimination issues.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This became a major confrontation that raised Aboriginal affairs high on the political agenda in the federal election later that year.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] One week after gaining office, the Whitlam government (1972–1975) established a Royal Commission into land rights for Aboriginal people in the Northern Territory under Justice Woodward.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The recommendations were framed in terms to enable application outside the Northern Territory.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The following year, the Fraser government (1975–1983) amended the Aboriginal Land (Northern Territory) Bill by introducing the Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Bill.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This bill was passed as the *Aboriginal Land Rights Act 1976*.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is significant however that this legislation was implemented at all, given the political allegiances of the Fraser government, and shows the level of community support for social justice for Aboriginal people at the time.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Whitlam government used its constitutional powers to overrule racially discriminatory state legislation.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On reserves in Queensland, Aboriginal people were forbidden to gamble, use foul language, undertake traditional cultural practices, indulge in adultery, or drink alcohol.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] They were also required to work without payment.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the Aboriginal Courts in Queensland the same official acted as judge as well as the prosecuting counsel.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Defendants almost invariably pleaded guilty as pleas of not guilty were more than likely to lead to a longer sentence.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Whitlam government, using the race power, enacted the *Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders (Queensland Discriminatory Laws) Act 1975* to override the state laws and eliminate racial discrimination against Aboriginal people.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, no federal government ever enforced this Act.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The race power was also used by the Whitlam government to introduce affirmative action in favour of Aboriginal people.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It established schemes whereby Aboriginal people could obtain housing, loans, emergency accommodation and tertiary education allowances.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It also increased funding for the Aboriginal Legal Service enabling twenty-five offices to be established throughout Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The race power gained in the 1967 referendum has been used in several other pieces of significant Federal legislation.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] One of the pieces of legislation enacted to protect the Gordon River catchment used the race power but applied it to all people in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The law prohibited anyone from damaging sites, relics and artefacts of Aboriginal settlement in the Gordon River catchment.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the Tasmanian Dam Case, the High Court held that even though this law applied to all people and not only to Aboriginal people, it still constituted a special law.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the 1992 Mabo judgment, the High Court of Australia established the existence of Native Title in Australian Common Law.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Using the race power, the Keating Government enacted the *Native Title Act 1993* and successfully defended a High Court challenge from the Queensland Government.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In granting the Commonwealth a broad power to legislate in regards to Indigenous Australians, responsibilities for areas traditionally the purview of the states (such as housing, education and healthcare) was shared between both branches of government.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] As a result, both levels have sought to blame the other for the continuing disadvantage of Indigenous Australians, while seeking to place the cost and responsibility to manage these issues on the other.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] When John Howard's Coalition government came to power in 1996, it intervened in the Hindmarsh Island bridge controversy in South Australia with legislation that introduced an exception to the *Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Heritage Protection Act 1984*, to allow the bridge to proceed.
[src:indigenous-australians/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The High Court decided, by a majority, that the amended s.51(xxvi) of the Constitution still allowed the Commonwealth parliament to make laws either for the benefit or to the detriment of a particular race.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] The first general election for the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly was held in the Northern Territory on Saturday 19 October 1974.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] The Country Liberal Party (CLP), formed a few months earlier from the merger of the territorial Country and Liberal parties, won a landslide victory with 49.01% of the vote.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] The Labor Party won 30.46% and independent candidates won 20.54%.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] The Country Liberals took 17 of the 19 assembly seats.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] The other two were held by independents; Dawn Lawrie won the seat of Nightcliff, and Ron Withnall won the seat of Port Darwin.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] Despite finishing second in the vote count, Labor failed to win any seats.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] Its support was spread out across the Territory, and was not concentrated in enough areas to translate into seats.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] As the territory was still being prepared for self-government, Country Liberal leader Goff Letts took the post of Majority Leader–equivalent to a state premier.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] Instead of a cabinet, a seven-person "executive" managed internal affairs.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] This would be the first of the CLP's eight consecutive election victories.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] The party would govern the territory for 28 years, one of the longest unbroken runs in government in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] Successful candidates are highlighted in the relevant colour.
[src:indigenous-australians/1974-northern-territory-general-election] Where there is possible confusion, an asterisk is used.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The **Australian republic referendum** held on 6 November 1999 was a two-question referendum to amend the Constitution of Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The first question asked whether Australia should become a republic, under a bi-partisan appointment model where the president would be appointed by the federal parliament with a two-thirds majority.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] This was the model that was endorsed by the Constitutional Convention, held in Canberra in February 1998.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The second question, generally deemed to be far less important politically, asked whether Australia should alter the Constitution to insert a preamble.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Since the early 1990s opinion polls had suggested that a majority of the electorate favoured a republic in principle.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Nonetheless, the republic referendum was defeated.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Australia is a constitutional monarchy under the Constitution of Australia adopted in 1901, with the duties of the monarch performed by a governor-general selected by the prime minister (although formally appointed by the monarch).
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Australian republicanism has existed since colonial times, though through much of the 20th century the monarchy remained popular.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] In the early 1990s, republicanism became an important political issue.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Australian Labor Party (ALP) Prime Minister Paul Keating indicated a desire to instigate a republic in time for the centenary of the Federation of Australia in 2001.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The opposition Liberal–National Coalition, led by Alexander Downer, though less supportive of the republic plan, promised to convene a constitutional convention to discuss the issue.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Under John Howard, the Coalition won the 1996 federal election and set the Convention date for February 1998.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The 1998 Australian Constitutional Convention debated the need for a change to the Constitution of Australia which would abolish the Australian monarchy.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The convention considered three categories of model for the selection of the head of state in an Australian republic: direct election, parliamentary election by a special majority, and appointment by a special council following prime ministerial nomination.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] "In principle" agreement was reached by a majority of delegates for an Australian republic model (though a minority bloc of monarchists dissented).
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Additionally, delegates endorsed a republic under a bipartisan appointment model as preferable to the existing constitutional arrangements (monarchists and some direct-election republicans abstained from the vote).
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The Convention also almost unanimously recommended to the prime minister and parliament that the agreed upon model be "put to the people" in a referendum to be held in 1999.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] First, Australians have traditionally been apprehensive about proposed constitutional change.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Before 1999, only eight of the 44 proposals put to a referendum, have been approved by the constitutionally required double majority – that is, (1) a majority in each of a majority of the six states and (2) a majority nationally.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] As Sir Robert Menzies explained following his failure to pass a referendum to ban the communist party, "to get an affirmative vote from the Australian people on a referendum proposal is one of the labours of Hercules".
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Second, public opinion varied widely on the issue, and was not a simple positive or negative reaction.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The process for change is seen as an important factor for the eventual outcome in a referendum.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Different groups within the republican cause expressed views as to which model was preferable.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Some were committed to one option exclusively.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The "Yes" campaign was headed by Malcolm Turnbull.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] It was notable for unlikely alliances between traditional opponents—for example, former Labor Prime Minister Gough Whitlam and former Liberal Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser gave joint statements.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Many other prominent Australians also endorsed the "Yes" vote, which led to claims that the movement was "elitist" in sentiment and supported by politicians rather than the public at large.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Viewing the case for a republic as fairly self-evident and broadly supported by the Australian populace, their advertising concentrated mainly on the positive symbolism of the republican case.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] One and all, they determined that Australians should have a republic and they used every device towards that end".
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The organised "No" campaign was led by a mixture of monarchist groups alongside some republican groups who did not feel that the proposed model was satisfactory; in particular, they thought that the people should elect the president.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Their advertising emphasised voting "No" to "this republic", implying to direct-election supporters that a model more to their preferences was likely to be put in the future.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The common elements within the "No" campaign were the view that the model proposed was undemocratic and would lead to a "politician's republic", playing to a general distrust of politicians.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] "No" campaigners called for further consultation, while remaining non-specific on what steps were needed to ensure this.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The model with an appointed head of state was the one endorsed by the Constitutional Convention and put forward at the referendum.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] It was broadly supported by both minimalist and establishment republicans, including almost all Labor and some conservative politicians.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Direct election republicans in the general community opposed the indirect elected model urging people to vote against the referendum.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] It was opposed by monarchists of both kinds.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Voting at the convention was recorded in Hansard.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Hansard shows that 73 delegates voted in favour, 57 against and 22 abstained.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Not one constitutional monarchist delegate voted in favour.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The policy of ACM and other monarchist groups was to oppose all republican models, including the minimalist McGarvie model.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Some conservatives argued that this would be the easiest model to defeat in a referendum and therefore should be supported at the convention.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Had the monarchists followed this advice, the McGarvie model would have prevailed at the convention.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] A number of republicans who supported direct election abstained from the vote (such as Ted Mack, Phil Cleary, Clem Jones and Andrew Gunter), thereby allowing the bi-partisan model to succeed.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] They reasoned that the model would be defeated at a referendum, and then a second referendum called with direct election as the model.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Although the motion was passed with a simple majority (excluding abstentions), the referendum model did not pass with an absolute majority (less than half of the total delegates supported the motion), a condition which the prime minister had indicated for a referendum.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Because the model was overwhelmingly supported by the republican delegates, the prime minister decided to put that model to the referendum, a decision acclaimed by the ARM delegates and the media.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Section 128 of the Constitution requires a "double majority" in a referendum to approve a constitutional amendment—a majority of votes in each of a majority of the states (i.e. at least four of the six), and a majority of all the electors voting.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Voters in the territories, as they do not live in states, count only towards the second of those majorities.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] 11,785,000 votes were cast, representing a voter turnout of 95.10%.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Of these, approximately 101,189 (0.86%) were informal, and not counted.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Both propositions failed on both of the voting requirements.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] There was no majority for "Yes" in any state, where the "Yes" vote for the republic ranged from 37.44% in Queensland to 49.84% in Victoria, and for the preamble ranged from 32.81% in Queensland to 42.46% in Victoria.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Overall, 54.87% voted "No" to the republic, and 60.66% to the preamble.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The highest "Yes" votes for the republic came from inner metropolitan areas.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Of Australia's 148 divisions, 42 voted "Yes", with Melbourne (70.92%), Sydney (67.85%), Melbourne Ports (65.90%), Grayndler (64.77%) and Fraser (64.46%) registering the highest "Yes" votes at division level.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Sydney, Melbourne, Canberra and Hobart voted in favour of the proposition for Australia to become a republic, in contrast to "No" votes in Adelaide, Brisbane, Gold Coast, Perth, Newcastle and Townsville.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Votes in opposition to the proposal came predominantly from rural and remote divisions, as well as many outer suburban areas.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The four divisions recording the highest "No" vote were in Queensland: Maranoa 77.16%, Blair 74.64%, Wide Bay 74.33% and Groom 72.58%.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Gwydir in rural New South Wales recorded the fifth-highest vote against the republic, with 72.21% level.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] With republican models of one form or another winning a majority in opinion polls prior to the referendum, it was expected that the republic referendum would pass.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] However, the question put was for a particular model of republic with a head of state appointed by Parliament.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] This was opposed by some supporters of a republic, who preferred a directly elected head of state.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Some of these, such as Phil Cleary, advocated that republic supporters vote "No" in order that a future referendum could be put on the directly elected model.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Some commentators—including the president of the Australian Republican Movement, Malcolm Turnbull—identified this split within the republican camp as a key reason for the referendum's failure.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] After the referendum, Malcolm Turnbull blamed Prime Minister John Howard in particular for the defeat and claimed: "Whatever else he achieves, history will remember him for only one thing.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] He was the Prime Minister who broke a nation's heart." Meanwhile, the leader of Australians for Constitutional Monarchy, Kerry Jones, called for citizens to accept the result and go forward "as a united nation".
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Later in 2006, Turnbull stated that the ARM had ultimately made the right choices, but that the referendum failed because Australians did not support indirect election and it would have been irresponsible for the ARM to have supported a direct election model.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Despite the hopes of more radical republicans such as Phil Cleary, the referendum defeat was generally viewed as a setback for the republican cause and calls for another referendum were ignored by the Howard government.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The Queen visited Australia the year following the referendum in 2000.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] During a speech she stated that "I respect and accept the outcome of the referendum.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] In the light of the result last November, I shall continue faithfully to serve as Queen of Australia under the Constitution to the very best of my ability".
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The Gillard Labor government, which took power in a hung parliament following the August 2010 election, indicated an intention not to revisit the issue of a vote for an Australian republic during the reign of Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The Liberal-National Coalition government in power following the September 2013 federal election was led by Tony Abbott who is a supporter of the constitutional monarchy.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] During Abbott's term as prime minister, Labor Opposition Leader Bill Shorten stated he believed it was time to "breathe new life into the dream of an Australian republic".
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] On 15 September 2015, Malcolm Turnbull, who had been chairman of the Australian Republican Movement from 1993 until 2000, succeeded Tony Abbott as leader of the Liberal Party, to become the prime minister of Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] For the first time, the prime minister and the federal Opposition Leader, as well as the eight state and territory premiers and chief ministers, were all self-declared republicans.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Turnbull has stated that he believes Australia should become a republic after the reign of Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Turnbull was later succeeded, on 24 August 2018, by Scott Morrison, who subsequently declared himself a constitutional monarchist, and re-hung a portrait of the Queen in the Prime Minister's office, which Turnbull had removed.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] Anthony Albanese, who was sworn in as prime minister in May 2022, is a convinced republican, going as far to appoint an Assistant Minister for the Republic.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] However, with the death of Queen Elizabeth II in September 2022, Albanese announced that he would not organise a referendum during his first term in office, out of respect for the late Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:indigenous-australians/1999-australian-republic-referendum] The Assistant Minister for the Republic position was not retained in the 2024 Cabinet reshuffle.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The **2000 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXVII Olympiad**, officially branded as **Sydney 2000**, and also known as the **Games of the New Millennium**, were an international multi-sport event held from 15 September to 1 October 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] It marked the second time the Summer Olympics were held in Australia, and in the Southern Hemisphere, the first being in Melbourne, in 1956.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Teams from 199 countries participated in the 2000 Games, which were the first to feature at least 300 events in its official sports program.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Games were estimated to have cost A$6.6 billion.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Juan Antonio Samaranch before the arrival of his successor Jacques Rogge.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The final medal tally at the 2000 Summer Olympics was led by the United States, followed by Russia and China with host Australia in fourth place overall.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Cameroon, Colombia, Latvia, Mozambique, and Slovenia won a gold medal for the first time in their Olympic histories, while Barbados, Kuwait, Kyrgyzstan, Macedonia, Saudi Arabia, and Vietnam won their first-ever Olympic medals.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The 2000 Games received universal acclaim, with the organisation, volunteers, sportsmanship, and Australian public being lauded in the international media.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Bill Bryson of *The Times* called the Sydney Games "one of the most successful events on the world stage", saying that they "couldn't be better".
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] James Mossop of the *Electronic Telegraph* called the Games "such a success that any city considering bidding for future Olympics must be wondering how it can reach the standards set by Sydney", while Jack Todd of the *Montreal Gazette* suggested that the "IOC should quit while it's ahead.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Admit there can never be a better Olympic Games, and be done with it," as "Sydney was both exceptional and the best".
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Australia will host the Summer Olympics in Brisbane in 2032, making it the first Asia-Pacific country to host the Summer Olympics three times.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Sydney won the right to host the Games on 24 September 1993, after being selected over Beijing, Berlin, Istanbul, and Manchester in four rounds of voting, at the 101st IOC Session in Monte Carlo, Monaco.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Beijing would later be selected to host the 2008 Summer Olympics eight years later on 13 July 2001 and the 2022 Winter Olympics twenty-two years later on 31 July 2015.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Brasília, Milan, and Tashkent made bids before deciding to withdraw during the bidding process.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Milan would later be selected to host the 2026 Winter Olympics along with Cortina d'Ampezzo twenty-six years later on 24 June 2019.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The *Oxford Olympics Study 2016* estimates the outturn cost of the Sydney 2000 Summer Olympics at US$5 billion in 2015 dollars and cost overrun at 90% in real terms.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Indirect capital costs are *not* included, such as for road, rail, airport infrastructure, hotel upgrades, or other business investments incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The cost for Sydney 2000 compares with a cost of US$4.6 billion for Rio 2016, US$40‍–‍44 billion for Beijing 2008, and US$51 billion for Sochi 2014, the most expensive Olympics in history.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games since 1960 is US$5.2 billion, average cost overrun is 176%.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In 2000, the Auditor-General of New South Wales reported that the Sydney Games cost A$6.6 billion, with a net cost to the public between A$1.7 and A$2.4 billion.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In the years leading up to the Games, funds were shifted from education and health programs to cover Olympic expenses.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] It has been estimated that the economic impact of the 2000 Olympics was that A$2.1 billion has been shaved from public consumption.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Economic growth was not stimulated to a net benefit, and, in the years after 2000, foreign tourism to NSW grew by less than tourism to Australia as a whole.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] A "multiplier" effect on broader economic development was not realised, as a simple "multiplier" analysis fails to capture that resources have to be redirected from elsewhere: the building of a stadium is at the expense of other public works such as extensions to hospitals.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Many venues that were constructed in Sydney Olympic Park failed financially in the years immediately following the Olympics to meet the expected bookings to meet upkeep expenses.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] It was only the 2003 Rugby World Cup that reconnected the park back to citizens.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In recent years, infrastructure costs for some facilities have been of growing concern to the NSW Government, especially facilities in Western Sydney.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Proposed metro and light rail links from Olympic Park to Parramatta have been estimated to cost in the same order of magnitude as the public expenditure on the Games.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Stadium Australia had been considered for demolition in 2017 by then NSW Premier Gladys Berejiklian, citing that the stadium was "built for an Olympics" but not for modern spectators.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The plan was scrapped in 2020 during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Dunc Gray Velodrome has also struggled to keep up its $500,000-per-year maintenance costs, although it is still used for track cycling events.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Although the Opening Ceremony was not scheduled until 15 September, the football competitions began with preliminary matches on 13 September.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Among the pre-ceremony fixtures, host nation Australia lost 1‍–‍0 to Italy at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, which was the main stadium for the 1956 Melbourne Olympics.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony began with a tribute to the pastoral heritage of the Australian stockmen and the importance of the stock horse in Australia's heritage.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] It was produced and filmed by the Sydney Olympic Broadcasting Organisation and the home nation broadcaster Seven Network.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] This was introduced by lone rider Steve Jefferys and his rearing Australian stock horse "Ammo".
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] At the cracking of Jefferys' stockwhip, a further 120 riders entered the stadium, their stock horses performing intricate steps, including forming the five Olympic Rings, sounded by a new version of the song that Bruce Rowland had previously composed for the 1982 film *The Man from Snowy River*.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Australian National Anthem was sung in the first verse by Human Nature and the second by Julie Anthony.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The cultural segments of the event take place with many aspects of the land and its people: the affinity of the mainly coastal-dwelling Australians with the sea that surrounds the Island Continent.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The indigenous inhabitation of the land, the coming of the First Fleet, the continued immigration from many nations, and the rural industry on which the economy of the nation was built, including a display representing the harshness of rural life based on the paintings of Sir Sidney Nolan.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Two memorable scenes were the representation of the heart of the country by 200 Aboriginal women from Central Australia who danced up "the mighty spirit of god to protect the Games" and the overwhelmingly noisy representation of the construction industry by hundreds of tap-dancing teenagers.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] A record 199 nations entered the stadium, with a record 80 of them winning at least one medal.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The only missing IOC member was Afghanistan, which was banned due to the extremist rule of the Taliban's oppression of women and its prohibition of sports.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The ceremony featured a unified entrance by the athletes of North and South Korea, using a specially designed unification flag: a white background flag with a blue map of the Korean Peninsula.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Four athletes from East Timor also marched in the parade of nations as individual Olympic athletes and marched directly before the host country.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Although the country-to-be had no National Olympic Committee then, they were allowed to compete under the Olympic Flag with country code IOA.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Governor-General, Sir William Deane, opened the games.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Olympic Flag was carried around the arena by eight former Australian Olympic champions: Bill Roycroft, Murray Rose, Liane Tooth, Gillian Rolton, Marjorie Jackson, Lorraine Crapp, Michael Wenden and Nick Green.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] During the raising of the Olympics Flag, the Olympic Hymn was sung by the Millennium Choir of the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of Australia in Greek.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Following this, Tina Arena sang a purpose-written pop song, *The Flame*.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony concluded with the lighting of the Olympic Flame, which was brought into the stadium by former Australian Olympic champion Herb Elliott.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The choice of Freeman, an Aboriginal woman, to light the flame was notable given the history of human rights abuses against Aboriginal people in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Following her lighting, Freeman was the subject of racial abuse from some Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The planned spectacular climax to the ceremony was delayed by the technical glitch of a computer switch which malfunctioned, causing the sequence to shut down by giving a false reading.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] This meant that the Olympic flame was suspended in mid-air for about four minutes rather than immediately rising up a water-covered ramp to the top of the stadium.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] When the cause of the problem was discovered, the program was overridden and the cauldron continued its course, and the ceremony concluded with a fireworks display.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The first medals of the Games were awarded in the women's 10-metre air rifle competition, which was won by Nancy Johnson of the United States.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The triathlon made its Olympic debut with the women's race.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Set in the surroundings of the Sydney Opera House, Brigitte McMahon representing Switzerland swam, cycled and ran to the first gold medal in the sport, beating the favoured home athletes such as Michelie Jones who won silver.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] McMahon only passed Jones in sight of the finish line.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The first star of the Games was 17-year-old Australian Ian Thorpe, who first set a new world record in the 400-metre freestyle final before competing in an exciting 4 × 100 m freestyle final.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Swimming the last leg, Thorpe passed the leading American team and arrived in a new world record time, two-tenths of a second ahead of the Americans.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In the same event for women, the Americans also broke the world record, finishing ahead of the Netherlands and Sweden.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Samaranch had to leave for home, as his wife was severely ill.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Upon arrival, his wife had already died.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Samaranch returned to Sydney four days later.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Olympic flag was flown at half-staff during the period as a sign of respect to Samaranch's wife.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Canadian Simon Whitfield sprinted away in the last 100 metres of the men's triathlon, becoming the inaugural winner in the event.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] On the cycling track, Robert Bartko beat fellow German Jens Lehmann in the individual pursuit, setting a new Olympic Record.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Leontien Zijlaard-van Moorsel set a world record in the semi-finals the same event for women.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In the swimming pool, American Tom Dolan beat the world record in the 400-metre medley, successfully defending the title he won in Atlanta four years prior.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Dutchwoman Inge de Bruijn also clocked a new world record, beating her own time in the 100 m butterfly final to win by more than a second.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The main event for the Australians on the fourth day of the Games was the 200 m freestyle.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Dutchman Pieter van den Hoogenband had broken the world record in the semi-finals, taking it from the new Australian hero Ian Thorpe, who came close to the world record in his semi-final heat.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] As the final race finished, Van den Hoogenband's time was exactly the same as in the semi-finals, finishing ahead of Thorpe by half a second.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] China won the gold medal in the men's team all-around gymnastics competition after being the runner-up in the previous two Olympics.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The other medals were taken by Ukraine and Russia, respectively.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Zijlaard-van Moorsel lived up to the expectations set by her world record in cycling in the semis by winning the gold medal.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] During the Women's Gymnastics All-Around, female athletes suffered damning scores and injuries due to improperly installed gymnastics equipment.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Gymnasts performing on the vault gave uncharacteristically poor performances and fell.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Officials blamed the series of falls and low scores on performance anxiety.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] It was not until Australian gymnast Allana Slater and her coach, Peggy Liddick, voiced concerns about the equipment that officials discovered the apparatus was five centimetres, or almost two inches, lower than it should have been.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] While athletes were given the opportunity to perform again, for some of them, the damage to their mental or physical health caused by the vault was irreparable.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Chinese gymnast Kui Yuanyuan and American gymnast Kristen Maloney both injured their legs while attempting to stick their landings, with Kui needing to be carried to an examination area and Maloney damaging a titanium rod that had recently been implanted in her shin.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Romanian gymnast Andreea Răducan ultimately took gold while her teammates, Simona Amânar and Maria Olaru took silver and bronze, respectively.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] By rowing in the winning coxless four, Steve Redgrave of Great Britain became a member of a select group who had won gold medals at five consecutive Olympics.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The swimming 4 x 100-metre medley relay of B.J.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Bedford, Megan Quann (Jendrick), Jenny Thompson and Dara Torres became the first women's relay team to finish in under four minutes, swimming 3:58 and setting a world record, claiming the gold medal for the United States.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Rulon Gardner, never an NCAA champion or a world medalist, beat Alexander Karelin of Russia to win gold in the super heavyweight class, Greco-Roman wrestling.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Karelin had won gold in Seoul, Barcelona and Atlanta.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Before this fight, he had never lost in international competition, had been unbeaten in all competitions in thirteen years, and had not surrendered a point in a decade.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Australian Cathy Freeman won the 400-metre final in front of a jubilant Sydney crowd at the Olympic Stadium, ahead of Lorraine Graham of Jamaica and Katharine Merry of Great Britain.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Freeman's win made her the first competitor in Olympic Games history to light the Olympic Flame and then go on to win a gold medal.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The attendance at the stadium was 112,524 – the largest attendance for any sport in Olympic Games history.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In a men's basketball pool match between the United States and France, the USA's Vince Carter made one of the most famous dunks in basketball history.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] After getting the ball off a steal, the 6'6"/1.98 m Carter drove to the basket, with 7'2"/2.18 m centre Frédéric Weis in his way.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Carter jumped, spread his legs in midair, scraped Weis' head on the way up, and dunked.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The French media dubbed the feat *le dunk de la mort* ("the dunk of death").
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Canadian flag at the athletes' village was lowered to half-mast, as Canadian athletes paid tribute to the former prime minister Pierre Trudeau after hearing of his death in Montreal (because of the time zone difference, it was 29 September in Sydney when Trudeau died).
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Canadian flag was flown at half-mast for the remainder of the Olympics, on orders from both IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch and Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The state funeral took place on 3 October, two days after the closing ceremony, allowing enough time for those concerned to head back to Canada after the Games and attend his funeral.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Cameroon won a historic gold medal over Spain in the Men's Olympic Football Final at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The game went to a penalty shootout, which was won by Cameroon 5‍–‍3.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The last event of the Games was the Men's Marathon, contested on a course that started in North Sydney.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The event was won by Ethiopian Gezahegne Abera, with Kenyan Erick Wainaina second, and Tesfaye Tola, also of Ethiopia, third.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] It was the first time since the 1968 Olympics that an Ethiopian won the gold medal in this event.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The closing ceremony commenced with Christine Anu performing her version of the Warumpi Band's song "My Island Home", with several Aboriginal dancers atop the Geodome Stage in the middle of the stadium, around which several hundred umbrella and lamp box kids created an image of Aboriginal Dreamtime.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Geodome Stage was used throughout the ceremony, which was a flat stage mechanically raised into the shape of a geode.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Although demonstration sports were abolished following the 1992 Summer Olympics, the Sydney Olympics featured wheelchair racing as exhibition events on the athletics schedule.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Special quarantine conditions were introduced to allow entry of horses into Australia to participate in equestrian events, avoiding the need for such events to take place elsewhere as had happened at the 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] 199 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated in the Sydney Games, two more than in the 1996 Summer Olympics; in addition, there were four Timorese Individual Olympic Athletes.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Eritrea, the Federated States of Micronesia and Palau made their Olympic debut this year.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Democratic Republic of the Congo was once again designated under that name, after it participated as Zaire from 1984 to 1996.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Afghanistan was the only 1996 participant (and the only existing NOC) that did not participate in the 2000 Olympics, having been banned due to the Taliban's totalitarian rule in Afghanistan, their oppression of women, and its prohibition of sports.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] 10,647 athletes from 199 NOCs participated in the 2000 Summer Olympics.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals in the 2000 Games.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The ranking in this table is based on information provided by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Some other sources may be inconsistent due to not taking into account all later doping cases.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] A number of quasi-government bodies were responsible for the construction, organisation and execution of the Sydney Games.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] These bodies are often collectively referred to as the "Olympic Family".
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The organisation of the 2000 Summer Paralympics was the responsibility of the Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee (SPOC).
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] However, much of the planning and operation of the Paralympic Games was outsourced to SOCOG such that most operational programmes planned both the Olympic and Paralympic Games.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The internal organisation of SOCOG evolved over the phases of the project and changed, sometimes radically, several times.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In late 1998, the design was principally functional.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The top two tiers below the CEO Sandy Hollway consisted of five groups (managed by Group General Managers and the Deputy CEO) and twenty divisions (managed by divisional General Managers), which in turn were further broken up into programmes and sub-programmes or projects.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In 1999, functional areas (FAs) broke up into geographic precinct and venue teams (managed by Precinct Managers and Venue Managers) with functional area staff reporting to both the FA manager and the venue manager.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Interstate Football division extant in 1998 was the first of these geographically based venue teams.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The origins of the volunteer program for Sydney 2000 dates back to the bid, as early as 1992.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] On 17 December 1992, a group of Sydney citizens interested in the prospect of hosting the 2000 Olympic and Paralympic Games gathered for a meeting at Sports House at Wentworth Park in Sydney.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] In the period leading up to 1999, after Sydney had won the bid, the small group of volunteers grew from approximately 42 to around 500.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] These volunteers became known as Pioneer Volunteers.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Pioneer Volunteer program was managed internally by SOCOG's Volunteer Services Department in consultation with prominent peak groups like The Centre for Volunteering (Volunteering and TAFE.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Some of the Pioneer Volunteers still meet every four months, an unseen legacy of the Games which brought together a community spirit not seen before.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] During the Olympic games, tens of thousands of volunteers (the official figure placed at 46,967) helped everywhere at the Olympic venues and elsewhere in the city.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] They were honoured with a parade like the athletes had a few days before.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The original festivals in Olympia celebrated both cultural events and physical feats.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The tradition continued with the first modern Olympics in 1896, and since then various cultural events have accompanied the sporting competition.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Starting with the 1996 Summer Olympics, a cycle of four arts festivals have been staged by each host country.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Sydney Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival that ran before and during the Olympics.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The festival event coordinator was David Gallen.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The first of the four festivals was the first edition of the Festival of the Dreaming, which was founded by artistic director Rhoda Roberts (who later co-directed segments of the Opening Ceremony), was held in 1997, as the first of four leading up to the Sydney Olympics.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Some events were held at the Sydney Opera House, and the festival included an Aboriginal cast performing Shakespeare's *A Midsummer Night's Dream*, as well as Samuel Beckett's *Waiting for Godot* performed in the Bundjalung language.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The second festival was "A Sea Change", in which artists and companies from Australia and Oceania explored "the influence of the sea on Australian life as a means to explore the changing political and cultural climates in Australia".
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The fourth and final festival, while featuring many international artists and companies, served as a showcase for the diversity and depth of the arts in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Opening four weeks before the Olympic Games, the Sydney 2000 Olympics Arts Festival ran until the last day of athletic competition, from 18 August to 1 October 2000.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Starting with an all-day Aboriginal welcoming ceremony, *Tubowgule* ("the Meeting of the Waters"), choreographed by Stephen Page, began at La Perouse beach near Botany Bay, and concluded at Bennelong Point, in the forecourt of Sydney Opera House.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] There, contemporary Indigenous dance company Bangarra Dance Theatre performed *Energy of Australia*.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The gala opening event for the festival was the musically pyrotechnical "Symphony of a Thousand" by Mahler at the Sydney SuperDome.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The festival included many performing arts events, mostly presented at the Sydney Opera House.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] There were also dance, singing, and drama performances, staged mainly at the Opera House but also at Her Majesty's Theatre and the Capitol Theatre.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] Only two plush toys of Fatso were made, one of which was placed in the Olympic Village; the plush was controversially smuggled into a medal ceremony by the Australian men's 4 × 200-metre relay team.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The character achieved a cult following, with some Australians preferring Fatso to the actual mascots.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] One of the Fatso plushes was auctioned for charity following the Games (being sold to Kerry Stokes, an executive of the Seven Network, for A$80,450), while a figure of Fatso was included in an display outside Stadium Australia that commemorated the Games' volunteers.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] A total of 750 gold, 750 silver and 780 bronze medals were minted for the Games.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The gold and silver medals contained 99.99 percent of pure silver.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The bronze medals were 99 percent bronze with one percent silver, they were made by melting down Australian one-cent and two-cent coins, which had been removed from circulation from 1992 onward.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The bouquets handed to medal recipients incorporated foliage from the Grevillea baileyana, also known as the white oak.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee awarded Sydney and its inhabitants with the "Pierre de Coubertin Trophy" in recognition of the collaboration and happiness shown by the people of Sydney during the event to all the athletes and visitors around the world.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] After the Games had ended, the New South Wales Police Force was granted use of the Olympic Rings in a new commendation and citation as the IOC consideration after having staged the "safest" Games ever.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] The Australian Entertainment Mo Awards (commonly known informally as the Mo Awards), were annual Australian entertainment industry awards.
[src:indigenous-australians/2000-summer-olympics] They recognise achievements in live entertainment in Australia from 1975 to 2016.
[src:indigenous-australians/2006-cannes-film-festival] The **59th Cannes Film Festival** was held from 17 to 28 May 2006.
[src:indigenous-australians/2006-cannes-film-festival] Chinese filmmaker Wong Kar-wai served as jury president for the main competition, becoming the first Chinese person to do so.
[src:indigenous-australians/2006-cannes-film-festival] English filmmaker Ken Loach won the Palme d'Or for the war drama film *The Wind That Shakes the Barley*.
[src:indigenous-australians/2006-cannes-film-festival] The official poster for the festival features a still image from the Wong Kar-wai's 2000 film *In the Mood for Love*, which won the Best Actor award at the 53rd edition.
[src:indigenous-australians/2006-cannes-film-festival] The festival opening film was *The Da Vinci Code* directed by Ron Howard.
[src:indigenous-australians/2006-cannes-film-festival] While *Transylvania* by Tony Gatlif was the closing film.
[src:indigenous-australians/2006-cannes-film-festival] This edition also marked the first time in three years that no American film, actor, actress, or filmmaker won any awards in Cannes.
[src:indigenous-australians/2006-cannes-film-festival] The Cannes Classics section highlights heritage cinema, re-discovered films, restored prints and theatrical, television or DVD releases of great films of the past.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Estimates from the 2021 Australian census show that there were almost one million Indigenous Australians, representing 3.8% of the Australian population.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] About 92% of Indigenous Australians identified as Aboriginal, 4% identified as Torres Strait Islander and 4% identified with both groups.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] About 84% spoke English at home and 9% spoke an Aboriginal or Torres Strait language at home.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians moved into what is now the Australian continent about 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the last glacial period, arriving by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The ancestors of today's Torres Strait Islanders arrived from what is now Papua New Guinea around 2,500 years ago and settled the islands on the northern tip of the Australian landmass.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Aboriginal Australians were complex hunter-gatherers with diverse economies and societies.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] There were about 600 tribes or nations and 250 languages with various dialects.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming and fish farming and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The extent to which some groups engaged in agriculture is controversial.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Torres Strait Islanders were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] They also developed agriculture on some of their islands.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Villages had appeared in their areas by the 14th century.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The Indigenous population prior to British settlement in 1788 has been estimated from 318,000 to more than 3,000,000.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] A population collapse, principally from new infectious diseases, followed British colonisation in 1788.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Massacres, frontier armed conflicts and competition over resources with British settlers also contributed to the decline of the Aboriginal population.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] From the 1930s, the Indigenous population began to recover and Indigenous communities founded organisations to advocate for their rights.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] From the 1960s Indigenous people won the right to vote in federal and state elections, and some won the return of parts of their traditional lands.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] In 1992 the High Court of Australia, in the Mabo Case, found that Indigenous native title rights existed in common law.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] By 2021 Indigenous Australians had exclusive or shared title to about 54% of the Australian land mass.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Since 1995 the Australian Aboriginal flag and the Torres Strait Islander flag have been official flags of Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] From the 19th to the mid-20th century, government policy removed many mixed heritage children from Aboriginal communities, with the intent to assimilate them to what had become the majority white culture.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] In 1997 the Australian Human Rights Commission found that the policy constituted genocide.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] There are a number of contemporary appropriate terms to use when referring to Indigenous peoples of Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The word *aboriginal* has been in the English language since at least the 16th century to mean "first or earliest known, indigenous".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] It comes from the Latin *ab* (from) and *origo* (origin, beginning).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The term was used in Australia as early as 1789 to describe its Aboriginal peoples.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] It became capitalised and was used as the common term to refer to both Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Today, the latter peoples are not included in this term.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The term "Aborigine" (as opposed to "Aboriginal") is often disfavoured, as it is regarded as having colonialist connotations.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] While the term "Indigenous Australians" has grown in popularity since the 1980s, many Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples dislike it.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] They feel that it is too generic and removes their distinct clan and people identity.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] However, many people think that the term is useful and convenient, and can be used where appropriate.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] In recent years, terms such as "First Nations", "First Peoples" and "First Australians" have become more common.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Being as specific as possible, for example naming the language group (such as Arrernte), or demonym relating to geographic area (such as Nunga), is preferred as a way to affirm and maintain a sense of identity.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] British colonists from their early settlement used the term "Black" to refer to Aboriginal Australians and later Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] While the term originally related to skin colour and was often used pejoratively, today the term is used to indicate Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander heritage or culture in general.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] It refers to any people of such heritage regardless of their level of skin pigmentation.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] In the 1970s, with a rise in Aboriginal activism, leaders such as Gary Foley proudly embraced the term "Black".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] For example, writer Kevin Gilbert's book of that time was entitled *Living Black*.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The book included interviews with several members of the Aboriginal community, including Robert Jabanungga, who reflected on contemporary Aboriginal culture.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] *Living Black* is also the name of an Australian TV news and current affairs program covering "issues affecting Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] It is presented and produced by Karla Grant, an Arrernte woman.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Use of the term "Black" varies depending on context, and its use may be deemed inappropriate.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Furthermore, the term sometimes causes confusion as it can refer to Indigenous Australians, other groups such as African Australians and Melanesian Australians (South Sea Islanders, Papua New Guinean Australians and Fijian Australians), or all Black people.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] A significant number of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people use the term "Blackfella" and its associated forms to refer to Aboriginal Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The term *blak* is sometimes used as part of a wider social movement (seen in terms such as "**Blaktivism**" and "Blak History Month").
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The term was coined in 1991 by photographer and multimedia artist Destiny Deacon, in an exhibition entitled *Blak lik mi*.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] For Deacon's 2004 exhibition at the Museum of Contemporary Art, *blak* was defined in a museum guide as: "a term used by some Aboriginal people to reclaim historical, representational, symbolical, stereotypical and romanticised notions of Black or Blackness.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Often used as ammunition or inspiration." Deacon said that removing the *c* from *black* to "de-weaponise the term 'black cunt'" was "taking on the 'colonisers' language and flipping it on its head".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Contemporary Aboriginal arts in the 21st century are sometimes referred to as a "Blak" arts movement, expressed in names such as BlakDance, BlakLash Collective, and the title of Thelma Plum's song and album, *Better in Blak*.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Melbourne has an annual Blak & Bright literary festival, Blak Dot Gallery, Blak Markets, and Blak Cabaret.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] "Aboriginal Australians" refers to the various peoples indigenous to mainland Australia and associated islands, excluding the Torres Strait Islands.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The term Aboriginal Australians includes many regional groups that may be identified under names based on local language, locality, or what they are called by neighbouring groups.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Groups can also evolve over time, and significant changes have occurred since colonisation.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The word "community" is often used to describe groups identifying by kinship, language, or belonging to a particular place or "country".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] An individual community may identify itself by many names, each of which can have alternative English spellings.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Throughout the history of the continent, there have been many different Aboriginal groups, each with its own individual language, culture, and belief structure.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] At the time of British settlement, there were over 200 distinct languages.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Torres Strait Islanders are the Indigenous Melanesian people of the Torres Strait Islands, which are part of the state of Queensland.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] They are ethnically distinct from the Aboriginal peoples of the rest of Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] Six percent of Indigenous Australians identify fully as Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] A further 4% of Indigenous Australians identify as having both Torres Strait Islander and Aboriginal heritage.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p01] The Torres Strait Islands comprise over 100 islands, which were annexed by Queensland in 1879.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians moved into what is now Oceania about 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the last glacial period, arriving by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The first phase of occupation of the Torres Strait Islands began about 4,000 years ago.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] By 2,500 years ago more of the islands were occupied and a distinctive Torres Strait Islander maritime culture emerged.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Agriculture also developed on some islands and by 700 years ago villages appeared.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Several settlements of humans in Australia have been dated around 49,000 years ago.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Luminescence dating of sediments surrounding stone artefacts at Madjedbebe, a rock shelter in northern Australia, indicates human activity as early as 65,000 years BP.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Genomic studies, however, suggest that the main wave of modern humans into Australia ancestral to Aboriginal Australians happened as recently as 37,000 to 50,000 years ago.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Accordingly, earlier groups either went extinct or contributed around ~2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Indigenous Australians and other Oceanians were probably part of the same southern route dispersal as the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians, Andamanese, and East Asians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The earliest anatomically modern human remains found in Australia (and outside of Africa) are those of Mungo Man; they have been dated at 42,000 years old.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The initial comparison of the mitochondrial DNA from the skeleton known as *Lake Mungo 3* (LM3) with that of ancient and modern Aboriginal peoples indicated that Mungo Man is not related to Australian Aboriginal peoples.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The sequence has been criticised as there has been no independent testing, and it has been suggested that the results may be due to posthumous modification and thermal degradation of the DNA.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] It is generally believed that Aboriginal people are the descendants of a single migration into the continent, a people that split from the ancestors of East Asians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Recent work with mitochondrial DNA suggests a founder population of between 1,000 and 3,000 women to produce the genetic diversity observed, which suggests that "initial colonisation of the continent would have required deliberate organised sea travel, involving hundreds of people".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Aboriginal people seem to have lived a long time in the same environment as the now extinct Australian megafauna.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Genetic studies have suggested that Aboriginal Australians largely descended from an Eastern Eurasian population wave during the Initial Upper Paleolithic, and are most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Melanesians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Aboriginal Australians also show affinity to Ancient Ancestral South Indians, the Andamanese people, as well as to East Asian peoples.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] 2011 shows that Aboriginal Australians have a lower proportion of European alleles compared to Asians, which they believe is indicative of a multiple dispersal model.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Genetically, while Aboriginal Australians are most closely related to Melanesian (including Papuan) people, McEvoy et al.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] 2010 believed there is also another component that could indicate Ancient Ancestral South Indian admixture or more recent European influence.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Research indicates a single founding Sahul group with subsequent isolation between regional populations which were relatively unaffected by later migrations from the Asian mainland, which may have introduced the dingo 4,000–5,000 years ago.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The research also suggests a divergence from the Papuan people of New Guinea and the Mamanwa people of the Philippines about 32,000 years ago, with a rapid population expansion about 5,000 years ago.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Bergström et al 2016 and Nagle et al 2016 could not replicate the 2012 study, noting that Indigenous Australians split from mainland Asia 50,000 years ago.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] 2017 study found that the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasian and Western Eurasian dates back to least 45,000 years ago, with Australasians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] 2024 noted that the divergence between Ancient East Eurasians and West Eurasians most likely occurred on the Persian Plateau >48,000 years ago, with East Eurasians dispersing throughout the Asia-Pacific region >45,000 years ago.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Aboriginal Australian men have haplogroup C-M347 in high frequencies with peak estimates ranging from 60.2% to 68.7%.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] 27% of them may carry K2* and approximately 29% of Aboriginal Australian males belong to subclades of K2b1, also known as M and S.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Aboriginal Australians possess deep rooted clades of both mtDNA haplogroup M and haplogroup N.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Aboriginal people lived as foragers and hunter-gatherers.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Although Aboriginal society was generally mobile, or semi-nomadic, moving according to the changing food availability found across different areas as seasons changed, the mode of life and material cultures varied greatly from region to region.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The greatest population density was to be found in the southern and eastern regions of the continent, the River Murray valley in particular.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] There is some evidence that, before outside contact, some groups of Aboriginal Australians had a complex subsistence system that was only recorded by the first European explorers.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] One early settler took notes on the life styles of the Wathaurung people whom he lived near in Victoria.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] He saw women harvesting murnong tubers, a native yam that is now almost extinct.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] However, the area that they were harvesting from was already cleared of other plants, making it easier to harvest murnong (also known as yam daisy) exclusively.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Along the northern coast of Australia, parsnip yams were harvested by leaving the bottom part of the yam still stuck in the ground so that it would grow again in the same spot.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Aboriginal peoples used slash-and-burn techniques to enrich the nutrients of their soil.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] However, sheep and cattle later brought over by Europeans would ruin this soil by trampling on it.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] They deliberately exchanged seeds to begin growing plants where they did not naturally occur.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Norman Tindale was able to draw an Aboriginal grain belt, detailing the specific areas where plants were once produced.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In terms of aquaculture, explorer Thomas Mitchell noted large stone fish traps on the Darling River at Brewarrina.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Each trap covers a pool, herding fish through a small entrance that would later be shut.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Traps were created at different heights to accommodate different water levels during floods and droughts.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Technology used by Indigenous Australian societies before European contact included weapons, tools, shelters, watercraft, and the message stick.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Weapons included boomerangs, spears (sometimes thrown with a woomera) with stone or fishbone tips, clubs, and (less commonly) axes.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Stone Age tools available included knives with ground edges, grinding devices, and eating containers.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Fibrecraft was well-developed, and fibre nets, baskets, and bags were used for fishing, hunting, and carrying liquids.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Trade networks spanned the continent, and transportation included canoes.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] A bark tent or lean-to is known as a humpy, gunyah, or wurley.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Clothing included the possum-skin cloak in the southeast, buka cloak in the southwest and riji (pearl shells) in the northeast.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] There is evidence that some Aboriginal populations in northern Australia regularly traded with Makassan fishermen from Indonesia before the arrival of Europeans.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Indigenous population prior to British settlement has been estimated from 300,000 to more than 3,000,000.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Recent archaeological finds suggest that a population of 500,000 to 750,000 could have been sustained, with some ecologists estimating that a population of one million to two million people was possible.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The geographic distribution of the pre-contact population is a matter of academic debate.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Pardoe argues that the distribution was similar to that of the current Australian population, the majority living in the south-east, centred along the Murray River.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] However, Evans suggests that the area which is now Queensland was the most densely populated.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Torres Strait peoples' fishing economy relied on boats, which they built themselves.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] There is also evidence of the construction of large, complex buildings on stilts and domed structures using bamboo, with thatched roofs, which catered for extended family members living together.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] British exploration of the Australian coastline began with the buccaneer William Dampier in 1688 and 1699.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Dampier was impressed neither by the country nor the people of the west Australian coast.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Almost a century later, the explorer James Cook mapped the east coast of Australia and claimed the territory for Britain in the name of King George III.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] They live in a Tranquillity which is not disturb'd by the Inequality of Condition".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Nevertheless, Cook also noted in his journal two men at Botany Bay who "seem'd resolved to oppose" his first landing.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] According to Cook, after one of the men threw a rock, Cook fired a musquet loaded with small shott, which struck him with little effect.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Some shott was lodged into one of the men's shields and was taken back to England by Cook, where it remains in the British Museum.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Cook spent a greater period of time among the Guugu Yimithirr people around modern Cooktown in Queensland, where his ship was nearly wrecked on the Great Barrier Reef.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Here relations were generally amicable and Cook recorded words from their language including "kangaroo", though a fight broke out when the British took turtles from the river without sharing them.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Peace was restored when an elder presented Cook with a broken-tipped spear as a peace offering – remembered as a first "act of reconciliation".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The encounter is commemorated annually by the Guugu Yimithirr to this day.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Cook's favourable impression of the East Coast of Australia led directly to the commencement of the British colonisation of Australia, commencing at Sydney in 1788.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] British colonisation of Australia began with the arrival of the First Fleet in Botany Bay, New South Wales, in 1788.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Settlements were subsequently established in Tasmania (1803), Victoria (1803), Queensland (1824), Western Australia (1826), and the Colony of South Australia (1836).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Australia was the exception to British imperial colonisation practices, in that no treaty was drawn up setting out terms of agreement between the settlers and native proprietors, as was the case in North America and New Zealand.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Many of the men on the First Fleet had had military experience among Native American tribes in North America, and tended to attribute to the Aboriginal people alien and misleading systems or concepts like chieftainship and tribe with which they had become acquainted in the northern hemisphere.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] British administrative control began in the Torres Strait Islands in 1862, with the appointment of John Jardine, police magistrate at Rockhampton, as Government Resident in the Torres Straits.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] He originally established a small settlement on Albany Island, but on 1 August 1864 he went to Somerset Island.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] English missionaries arrived on Erub (Darnley Island) on 1 July 1871.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1872 the boundary of Queensland was extended to include Thursday Island and some other islands in Torres Strait within 60 miles (97 km) of the Queensland coast, and in 1879 Queensland annexed the other islands, which became part of the British colony of Queensland.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] One immediate consequence was a series of epidemics of European diseases such as measles, smallpox and tuberculosis.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the 19th century, smallpox was the principal cause of Aboriginal deaths, and vaccinations of the "native inhabitants" had begun in earnest by the 1840s.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] This smallpox epidemic in 1789 is estimated to have killed up to 90% of the Darug people.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Some scholars have attributed it to European settlers, but it is also argued that Macassan fishermen from South Sulawesi and nearby islands may have introduced smallpox to Australia before the arrival of Europeans.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] A third suggestion is that the outbreak was caused by contact with members of the First Fleet.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] A fourth theory is that the epidemic was of chickenpox, not smallpox, carried by members of the First Fleet, and to which the Aboriginal people also had no immunity.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Moreover, Aboriginal people were infected with sexually transmitted infections, especially syphilis and gonorrhea.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Another consequence of British colonisation was European seizure of land and water resources, with the decimation of kangaroo and other food sources which continued throughout the 19th and early 20th centuries as rural lands were converted for sheep and cattle grazing.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Settlers also participated in the rape and forcible prostitution of Aboriginal women.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Some Europeans, for example escaped convicts, lived in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1834 there occurred the first recorded use of Aboriginal trackers, who proved very adept at navigating their way through the Australian landscape and finding people.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] During the 1860s, Tasmanian Aboriginal skulls were particularly sought internationally for studies into craniofacial anthropometry.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The skeleton of Truganini, a Tasmanian Aboriginal who died in 1876, was exhumed within two years of her death despite her pleas to the contrary by the Royal Society of Tasmania, and later placed on display.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Campaigns continue to have Aboriginal body parts returned to Australia for burial; Truganini's body was returned in 1976 and cremated, and her ashes were scattered according to her wishes.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Place names sometimes reveal discrimination, such as Mount Jim Crow in Rockhampton, Queensland (now Mount Baga), as well as racist policies, like Brisbane's Boundary Streets, which used to indicate boundaries where Aboriginal people were not allowed to cross during certain times of the day.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] There is ongoing discussion about changing many of these names.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Throughout most of the 19th and 20th centuries, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people had their lives under the jurisdiction of various state-based protection laws.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] These Acts of Parliament appointed Protectors of Aborigines and Aboriginal Protection Boards, whose role was to control the lives of Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Wages were controlled by the Protectors, and Indigenous Australians received less income than their non-Indigenous counterparts in employment.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] During this time, many Aboriginal people were victims of slavery by colonists alongside Pacific Islander peoples who were kidnapped from their homes, in a practice known as blackbirding.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Between 1860 and 1970, under the guise of protectionist policies, people, including children as young as 12, were forced to work on properties where they worked under horrific conditions and most did not receive any wages.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the pearling industry, Aboriginal peoples were bought for about 5 pounds, with pregnant Aboriginal women "prized because their lungs were believed to have greater air capacity".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Aboriginal prisoners in the Aboriginal-only prison on Rottnest Island, many of whom were there on trumped up charges, were chained up and forced to work.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1971, 373 Aboriginal men were found buried in unmarked graves on the island.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Up until June 2018, the former prison was being used as holiday accommodation.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] From 1810, Aboriginal peoples were moved onto mission stations, run by churches and the state.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] After this period of protectionist policies that aimed to segregate and control Aboriginal populations, in 1937 the Commonwealth government agreed to move towards assimilation policies.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] These policies aimed to integrate Aboriginal persons who were "not of full blood" into the white community in an effort to eliminate the "Aboriginal problem".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] As part of this, there was an increase in the number of children forcibly removed from their homes and placed with white people, either in institutions or foster homes.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] As part of the colonisation process, there were many conflicts and clashes between colonists and Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people across the continent and islands.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In Queensland, the killing of Aboriginal peoples was largely perpetrated by civilian "hunting" parties and the Native Police, armed groups of Aboriginal men who were recruited at gunpoint and led by government officers to eliminate Aboriginal resistance.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] There is evidence that massacres of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, which began with arrival of British colonists, continued until the 1930s.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Researchers at the University of Newcastle under Lyndall Ryan have been mapping the massacres. as of 2020 they have mapped almost 500 places where massacres happened, with 12,361 Aboriginal people killed and 204 Colonists killed, numbering at least 311 massacres over a period of about 140 years.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] After losing a significant number of their social unit in one blow, the survivors were left very vulnerable – with reduced ability to gather food, reproduce, or fulfill their ceremonial obligations, as well as defend themselves against further attack.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Estimating the total number of deaths during the frontier wars is difficult due to lack of records and the fact that many massacres of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander were kept secret.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] It is often quoted that 20,000 Aboriginal Australians and 2000 colonists died in the frontier wars; however, recent research indicates at least 40,000 Aboriginal dead and 2,000 to 2,500 settlers dead.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Other research indicates a minimum of 65,000 Aboriginal peoples may have been killed in Queensland alone.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] There have been arguments over whether deaths of Aboriginal peoples, particularly in Tasmania, as well as the forcible removal of children from Aboriginal communities, constitutes genocide.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] According to the analysis of Justice Ronald Wilson in the Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Report Australia's policy of forcible removal was genocidal in nature.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Wilson states that "Genocide can be committed by means other than actual physical extermination.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] It is committed by the forcible transfer of children, provided the other elements of the crime are established." He points out that "Genocide is committed even when the destruction has not been carried out.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] There are few memorials in Australia acknowledging the widespread massacres of Aboriginal Peoples, and no memorials describing it as genocide.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The forcible removal of these children occurred in the period between approximately 1871 and 1969, although in some places children were still being taken in the 1970s.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] By 1900, the recorded Indigenous population of Australia had declined to approximately 93,000.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] However, this was only a partial count, as both Aboriginal people and Torres Strait Islanders were poorly covered, with desert Aboriginal peoples not counted at all until the 1930s.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] During the first half of the twentieth century, many Indigenous Australians worked as stockmen on sheep stations and cattle stations for extremely low wages.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Indigenous population continued to decline, reaching a low of 74,000 in 1933 before numbers began to recover.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] By 1995, population numbers had reached pre-colonisation levels, and in 2010 there were around 563,000 Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Although, as British subjects, all Indigenous Australians were nominally entitled to vote, generally only those who merged into mainstream society did so.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Only Western Australia and Queensland specifically excluded Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from the electoral rolls.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Despite efforts to bar their enlistment, over 1,000 Indigenous Australians fought for Australia in the First World War.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] 1934 saw the first appeal to the High Court by an Aboriginal Australian, and it succeeded.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Dhakiyarr was found to have been wrongly convicted of the murder of a white policeman, for which he had been sentenced to death; the case focused national attention on Aboriginal rights issues.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1938, the 150th anniversary of the arrival of the British First Fleet was marked as a Day of Mourning and Protest at an Aboriginal meeting in Sydney, and has since become marked around Australia as "Invasion Day" or "Survival Day" by Aboriginal protesters and their supporters.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Hundreds of Indigenous Australians served in the Australian armed forces during World War Two – including with the Torres Strait Light Infantry Battalion and The Northern Territory Special Reconnaissance Unit, which were established to guard Australia's North against the threat of Japanese invasion.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] However, most were denied pension rights and military allotments, except in Victoria, where each case was judged individually, without a blanket denial of rights accruing from their service.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The 1960s was a pivotal decade in the assertion of Aboriginal rights and a time of growing collaboration between Aboriginal activists and white Australian activists.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1962, Commonwealth legislation guaranteed Aboriginal people the right to vote in Commonwealth elections, which had previously been denied to Indigenous people in Queensland and Western Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] A group of University of Sydney students organised a bus tour of western and coastal New South Wales towns in 1965 to raise awareness of the state of Aboriginal health and living conditions.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] This Freedom Ride also aimed to highlight the social discrimination faced by Aboriginal people and encourage Aboriginal people themselves to resist discrimination.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] As mentioned above, Indigenous Australians received lower wages than their non-Indigenous counterparts in employment.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people in Queensland in particular had their income quarantined by the Protector and were allowed a minimal amount of their income.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1966, Vincent Lingiari led the famous Wave Hill walk-off (Gurindji strike) of Indigenous employees of Wave Hill Station in protest against poor pay and conditions (later the subject of the Paul Kelly and Kev Carmody song "From Little Things Big Things Grow").
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Since 1999, the Queensland Government, under pressure from the Queensland Council of Unions, has established a number of schemes to give any earned income not received at the time back to Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The referendum passed with 90.77% voter support.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the controversial 1971 Gove land rights case, Justice Blackburn ruled that Australia had been *terra nullius* before British settlement, and that no concept of native title existed in Australian law.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Following the 1973 Woodward commission, in 1975 the federal government under Gough Whitlam drafted the Aboriginal Land Rights Bill.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1985, the Australian government returned ownership of Uluru (Ayers Rock) to the Pitjantjatjara Aboriginal people.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1992, the High Court of Australia reversed Justice Blackburn's ruling and handed down its decision in the Mabo Case, declaring the previous legal concept of *terra nullius* to be invalid and confirming the existence of native title in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Indigenous Australians began to serve in parliaments from the late 1960s.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1971, Neville Bonner joined the Australian Senate as a Senator for Queensland for the Liberal Party, becoming the first Indigenous Australian in the Federal Parliament.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] A year later, the Aboriginal Tent Embassy was established on the steps of Parliament House in Canberra.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1976, Sir Douglas Nicholls was appointed as the 28th Governor of South Australia, the first Aboriginal person appointed to vice-regal office.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the general election of 2010, Ken Wyatt of the Liberal Party became the first Indigenous Australian elected to the Australian House of Representatives.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the general election of 2016, Linda Burney of the Australian Labor Party became the second Indigenous Australian, and the first Indigenous Australian woman, elected to the Australian House of Representatives.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] She was immediately appointed Shadow Minister for Human Services.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In sport Evonne Goolagong Cawley became the world number-one ranked tennis player in 1971 and won 14 Grand Slam titles during her career.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1973 Arthur Beetson became the first Indigenous Australian to captain his country in any sport when he first led the Australian National Rugby League team, the Kangaroos.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1982, Mark Ella became captain of the Australia national rugby union team.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 2000, Aboriginal sprinter Cathy Freeman lit the Olympic flame at the opening ceremony of the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, and went on to win the 400 metres at the Games.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 2019, tennis player Ashleigh Barty was ranked world number one.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1984, a group of Pintupi people who were living a traditional hunter-gatherer desert-dwelling life were tracked down in the Gibson Desert in Western Australia and brought in to a settlement.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] They are believed to have been the last uncontacted people in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] During this period, the federal government enacted a number of significant, but controversial, policy initiatives in relation to Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] A representative body, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC), was set up in 1990.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Reconciliation between non-Indigenous and Indigenous Australians became a significant issue in Australian politics in the late 20th century.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1991, the Council for Aboriginal Reconciliation was established by the federal government to facilitate reconciliation.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] An inquiry into the Stolen Generations was launched in 1995 by the Keating government, and the final report delivered in 1997 – the *Bringing Them Home* report – estimated that around 10% to 33% of all Aboriginal children had been separated from their families for the duration of the policies.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The succeeding Howard government largely ignored the recommendations provided by the report, one of which was a formal apology to Aboriginal Australians for the Stolen Generations.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The republican model, as well as a proposal for a new Constitutional preamble which would have included the "honouring" of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, was put to referendum but did not succeed.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] On 13 February 2008, Prime Minister Kevin Rudd issued a formal apology to Australia's Indigenous peoples, on behalf of the federal government of Australia, for the suffering caused by the Stolen Generations.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 2001, the Federal Government dedicated Reconciliation Place in Canberra.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] On 13 February 2008, Prime Minister Kevin Rudd reversed Howard's decision and issued a public apology to members of the Stolen Generations on behalf of the Australian Government.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] ATSIC was abolished by the Australian Government in 2004 amidst allegations of corruption.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Northern Territory National Emergency Response (also known as the Intervention) was launched in 2007 by the government of Prime Minister John Howard, in response to the *Little Children are Sacred* report into allegations of child abuse among Aboriginal communities in the NT.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The government banned alcohol in prescribed communities in the Territory; quarantined a percentage of welfare payments for essential goods purchasing; dispatched additional police and medical personnel to the region; and suspended the permit system for access to Aboriginal communities.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In addition to these measures, the army were released into communities and there were increased police powers, which were later further increased with the so-called "paperless arrests" legislation.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 2010, United Nations Special Rapporteur James Anaya found the Emergency Response to be racially discriminatory, and said that aspects of it represented a limitation on "individual autonomy".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] These findings were criticised by the government's Indigenous Affairs Minister Jenny Macklin, the Opposition and Indigenous leaders like Warren Mundine and Bess Price.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The policy has been criticised by organisations such as Amnesty International and other groups, including on the basis that it maintains "racially-discriminatory" elements of the *Emergency Response Act* and continues control by the federal government over "Aboriginal people and their lands".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 2010, the federal government appointed a panel comprising Indigenous leaders, other legal experts and some members of parliament (including Ken Wyatt) to provide advice on how best to recognise Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples in the federal Constitution.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The panel's recommendations, reported to the federal government in January 2012, included deletion of provisions of the Constitution referencing race (Section 25 and Section 51(xxvi)), and new provisions on meaningful recognition and further protection from discrimination.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Subsequently, a proposed referendum on Constitutional recognition of Indigenous Australians was ultimately abandoned in 2013.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The *Uluru Statement from the Heart* was released 26 May 2017 by delegates to an Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Referendum Convention, held near Uluru in Central Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The statement calls for a "First Nations Voice" in the Australian Constitution and a "Makarrata Commission" to supervise a process of "agreement-making" and "truth-telling" between government and Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The statement references the 1967 referendum which brought about changes to the Constitution to include Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates that in 2021 there were 983,700 Indigenous Australians, of whom 901,700 were Aboriginal, 39,540 Torres Strait Islander, and 39,540 identifying as both Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Indigenous population from 1971 to 2021 are given below.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] These are based on initial census counts and have not been adjusted for undercounting and other factors.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Over time Australia has used various means to determine membership of ethnic groups such as lineage, blood quantum, birth and self-determination.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The ruling was a three-part definition comprising descent, self-identification and community identification.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The first part – descent – was genetic descent and unambiguous, but led to cases where a lack of records to prove ancestry excluded some.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Self- and community identification were more problematic as they meant that an Indigenous person separated from his or her community due to a family dispute could no longer identify as Aboriginal.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] As a result, there arose court cases throughout the 1990s where excluded people demanded that their Aboriginality be recognised.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] As a result, lower courts refined the High Court test when subsequently applying it.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In 1998 Justice Merkel held in *Shaw v Wolf* that Aboriginal descent is "technical" rather than "real" – thereby eliminating a genetic requirement.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] This decision established that anyone can classify him or herself legally as an Aboriginal, provided he or she is accepted as such by his or her community.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Indigenous Australians have been counted in every census albeit only approximately and using inconsistent definitions.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] As a consequence of section 127, Indigenous Australians in remote areas uninhabited by non-Indigenous Australians were not counted prior to 1967 in censuses and sometimes estimated.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Post 1967, Torres Strait Islanders were considered a separate Indigenous people.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Prior to 1947, Torres Strait Islanders were considered to be Aboriginal in censuses.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the 1947 census, Torres Strait Islanders were considered to be Polynesian and in the 1954 and 1961 censuses were considered to be Pacific Islanders.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the 1966 census, Torres Strait Islanders were considered to be Aboriginal.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] A "Commonwealth working definition" for Indigenous Australians was developed from 1968 and endorsed by Cabinet in 1978 which contains elements of descent, self-identification and community recognition in contrast to the earlier preponderance of Aboriginal blood definition.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] As there is no formal procedure for any community to record acceptance, the primary method of determining Indigenous population is from self-identification on census forms.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The Australian Census includes counts based on questions relating to individuals' self-identification as Aboriginal, Torres Strait Islander, or of both origins.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Owing to various difficulties which lead to under-counting, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) follows a set method to estimate total numbers.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] The 2006 Australian census showed growth in the Indigenous population (recorded as 517,000) at twice the rate of overall population growth since 1996, when the Indigenous population stood at 283,000.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the 2011 census, there was a 20% rise in people who identify as Aboriginal.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the 2016 census, there was another 18.4% rise on the 2011 figure.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] 590,056 respondents identified themselves as Aboriginal, 32,345 Torres Strait Islander, and a further 26,767 both Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the 2021 Australian census, 812,000 people identified as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander, representing 3.2% of the population.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] However, the net undercount of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people was 17.4%, and the estimated Indigenous population is around 952,000 to 1,000,000, or just under 4 per cent of the total population.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] Growth to 2016 was mainly in major cities and along the eastern coast of Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p02] In the 2016, over 33% of the Indigenous population lived in major cities, compared with about 75% of the non-Indigenous population, with a further 24% in "inner regional" areas (compared with 18%), 20% in "outer regional" (8%), while nearly 18% lived in "remote" or "very remote" areas (2%).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Nine percent spoke an Australian Indigenous language at home.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago but it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Indigenous languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal and Torres Strait Island languages with the most speakers are Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole) (7,596 speakers), Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language which could not be further defined or classified.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Several extinct Indigenous languages are being reconstructed.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] For example, the last fluent speaker of the Ngarrindjeri language died in the late 1960s; using recordings and written records as a guide, a Ngarrindjeri dictionary was published in 2009, and the Ngarrindjeri language is today spoken in complete sentences.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Aboriginal languages are divided into two main groups: the Pama–Nyungan languages which is spoken across about 90% of the continent, and the non-Pama–Nyungan.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Recent research suggests that an ancestor language to all Aboriginal languages was spoken 12,000 years ago and spread across the continent in the past 6,000 years.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Three languages are spoken on the islands of the Torres Strait, within Australian territory, by the Melanesian inhabitants of the area: Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole) (7,596 speakers used the language at home in 2021), Kalaw Lagaw Ya (875 speakers) and Meriam Mir (256 speakers).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Meriam Mir is a Papuan language, while Kalaw Lagaw Ya is an Australian language.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol and Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole) are among the strongest and fastest-growing Indigenous languages.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia, and Torres Strait Creole in Queensland and south-west Papua.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Cross-cultural miscommunication can sometimes occur between Indigenous and non-Indigenous peoples.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] According to Michael Walsh and Ghil'ad Zuckermann, Western conversational interaction is typically "dyadic", between two particular people, where eye contact is important and the speaker controls the interaction; and "contained" in a relatively short, defined time frame.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] However, traditional Aboriginal conversational interaction is "communal", broadcast to many people, eye contact is not important, the listener controls the interaction; and "continuous", spread over a longer, indefinite time frame.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In Aboriginal communities knowledge and decision making is shared between tribal elders.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Travellers had to seek elder recognition and acknowledge local Elders – this is increasingly practiced in public events in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Within Aboriginal belief systems, a formative epoch known as "the Dreaming" or "the Dreamtime" stretches back into the distant past when the creator ancestors known as the First Peoples travelled across the land, and naming as they went.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Indigenous Australia's oral tradition and religious values are based upon reverence for the land and a belief in this Dreamtime.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Dreaming is at once both the ancient time of creation and the present-day reality of Dreaming.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Different language and cultural groups each had their own belief structures; these cultures overlapped to a greater or lesser extent, and evolved over time.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Knowledge contained in the Dreaming has been passed down through different stories, songlines, dances and ceremonies, and even today provides a framework for ongoing relationships, kinship responsibilities and looking after country.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Traditional healers (known as Ngangkari in the Western desert areas of Central Australia) were highly respected men and women who not only acted as healers or doctors, but were generally also custodians of important Dreaming stories.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Torres Strait Islander people have their own traditional belief systems.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Stories of the Tagai represent Torres Strait Islanders as sea people, with a connection to the stars, as well as a system of order in which everything has its place in the world.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Some Torres Strait Islander people share beliefs similar to the Aboriginal peoples' Dreaming and "Everywhen" concepts, passed down in oral history.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Christianity and European culture have had a significant impact on Indigenous Australians, their religion and their culture.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] As in many colonial situations, the churches both facilitated the loss of Indigenous culture and religion and also facilitated its maintenance.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In some cases, such as at Hermannsburg, Northern Territory and Piltawodli in Adelaide, the work of missionaries laid the foundations for later language revival.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The German missionaries Christian Teichelmann and Schürmann went to Adelaide and taught the local Kaurna people only in their own language and created textbooks in the language.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] However, some missionaries taught only in English, and some Christian missions were involved in the placement of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children after they were removed from their parents upon orders of the government, and are therefore implicated in the Stolen Generations.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The involvement of Christians in Aboriginal affairs has evolved significantly since 1788.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Churches became involved in mission work among Aboriginal peoples in the 19th century as Europeans came to control much of the continent, and the majority of the population was eventually converted.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Colonial clergy such as Sydney's first Catholic archbishop, John Bede Polding, strongly advocated for Aboriginal rights and dignity.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Around the year 2000, many churches and church organisations officially apologised for past failures to adequately respect Indigenous cultures and address the injustices of the dispossession of Indigenous people.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] A small minority of Aboriginal people are followers of Islam as a result of intermarriage with "Afghan" camel drivers brought to Australia in the late 19th and early 20th century to help explore and open up the interior.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] From the 1870s, Christianity spread throughout the Torres Strait Islands, and it remains strong today among Torres Strait Islander people everywhere.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The London Missionary Society mission led by Rev.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Samuel Macfarlane arrived on Erub (Darnley Island) on 1 July 1871, establishing its first base in the region there.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Islanders refer to this as "The Coming of the Light", or "Coming of Light" and all Island communities celebrate the occasion annually on 1 July.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] However the coming of Christianity did not spell the end of the people's traditional beliefs; their culture informed their understanding of the new religion, as the Christian God was welcomed and the new religion was integrated into every aspect of their everyday lives.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In the 2016 Census, Australia's Indigenous and non-Indigenous population were broadly similar with 54% (vs 55%) reporting a Christian affiliation, while less than 2% reported traditional beliefs as their religion, and 36% reported no religion.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The proportion of Indigenous people who reported no religion has increased gradually since 2001, standing at 36% in 2016.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] According to "Table 8: Religious Affiliation by Indigenous Status", 347,572 Indigenous people (out of the total 649,171 in Australia) declared an affiliation to some form of Christianity, with a higher proportion of Torres Strait Islander than Aboriginal people in this number.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] 7,773 reported traditional beliefs; 1,511 Islam; other religions numbered less than 1,000 each.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] However the question is optional; 48,670 did not respond, and in addition, nearly 4,000 were reported as "inadequately described".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Australia has a tradition of Aboriginal art which is thousands of years old, the best known forms being Australian rock art and bark painting.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Evidence of Aboriginal art can be traced back at least 30,000 years, with examples of ancient rock art throughout the continent.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Some of these are in national parks such as those of the UNESCO listed sites at Uluru and Kakadu National Park in the Northern Territory, but examples can also within protected parks in urban areas such as at Ku-ring-gai Chase National Park in Sydney.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Sydney rock engravings are between 5000 and 200 years old.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Murujuga, in north-western Western Australia was heritage-listed in 2007 and inscribed as a World Heritage Site in July 2025.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In terms of age and abundance, cave art in Australia is comparable to that of Lascaux and Altamira (Upper Paleolithic sites in Europe), and Aboriginal art is believed to be the oldest continuing tradition of art in the world.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] There are three major regional styles: the geometric style found in Central Australia, Tasmania, the Kimberley and Victoria, known for its concentric circles, arcs and dots; the simple figurative style found in Queensland; and the complex figurative style found in Arnhem Land and the Kimberley.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] These designs generally carry significance linked to the spirituality of the Dreamtime.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Paintings were usually created in earthy colours, from paint made from ochre.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Such ochres were also used to paint their bodies for ceremonial purposes.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Several styles of Aboriginal art have developed in modern times, including the watercolour paintings of the Hermannsburg School and the acrylic Papunya Tula "dot art" movement.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Some notable Aboriginal artists include William Barak (c.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Since the 1970s, Indigenous artists have employed the use of acrylic paints – with styles such as that of the Western Desert Art Movement becoming globally renowned 20th-century art movements.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The National Gallery of Australia exhibits a great many Indigenous art works, including those of the Torres Strait Islands who are known for their traditional sculpture and headgear.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Aboriginal art has influenced many non-Indigenous artists, such as Margaret Preston (1875–1963) and Elizabeth Durack (1915–2000).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Music and dance have formed an integral part of the social, cultural and ceremonial observances of people through the millennia of the individual and collective histories of Australian Indigenous peoples to the present day.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Around 1950, the first research into Aboriginal music was undertaken by the anthropologist A.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Elkin, who recorded Aboriginal music in Arnhem Land.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The various Aboriginal peoples developed unique musical instruments and styles.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The didgeridoo, which is widely thought to be a stereotypical instrument of Aboriginal people, was traditionally played by Aboriginal men of the eastern Kimberley region and Arnhem Land (such as the Yolngu).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Bullroarers and clapsticks were used across Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Songlines relate to the Dreamtime in Aboriginal culture, overlapping with oral lore.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Corroboree is a generic word to explain different genres of performance, embracing songs, dances, rallies and meetings of various kinds.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Indigenous musicians have been prominent in various contemporary styles of music, including creating a sub-genre of rock music as well as participating in pop and other mainstream styles.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Hip hop music is helping preserve some Indigenous languages.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Aboriginal Centre for the Performing Arts in Brisbane teaches acting, music and dance, and the Bangarra Dance Theatre is an acclaimed contemporary dance company.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] For Torres Strait Islander people, singing and dancing is their "literature" – "the most important aspect of Torres Strait lifestyle.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Torres Strait Islanders preserve and present their oral history through songs and dances;... the dances act as illustrative material and, of course, the dancer himself is the storyteller" (Ephraim Bani, 1979).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] There was no written form of the many languages spoken by Indigenous peoples before colonisation.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] A letter to Governor Arthur Phillip written by Bennelong in 1796 is the first known work written in English by an Aboriginal person.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Before that, Indigenous societies were oral.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Their cultural isolation for most of the last 65,000 years proved a perfect situation for the construction and preservation of some of the world's oldest stories.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The historic Yirrkala bark petitions of 1963 are the first traditional Aboriginal documents recognised by the Australian Parliament.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In the 20th century, David Unaipon (1872–1967), known as the first Aboriginal author, is credited for providing the first accounts of Aboriginal mythology written by an Aboriginal person, in his *Legendary Tales of the Aborigines* (1924–1925).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Oodgeroo Noonuccal (1920–1995) was a famous Aboriginal poet, writer and rights activist, credited with publishing the first book of verse by an Aboriginal author, *We Are Going* (1964).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Sally Morgan's novel *My Place* (1987) was considered a breakthrough memoir in terms of bringing Indigenous stories to a wider audience.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The talents of playwrights Jack Davis and Kevin Gilbert were recognised.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Poetry by Indigenous poets, including traditional song-poetry – ranging from sacred to everyday – has been published since the late 20th century.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Writers coming to prominence in the 21st century include Alexis Wright; Kim Scott (twice winner of the Miles Franklin Award); Tara June Winch; Melissa Lucashenko; playwright and comedy writer Nakkiah Lui; in poetry Yvette Holt; and in popular fiction Anita Heiss.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Leading activists Marcia Langton, who wrote *First Australians* (2008) and Noel Pearson (*Up From the Mission*, 2009) are as of 2020 active contemporary contributors to Australian literature.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Journalist Stan Grant has written several non-fiction works on what it means to be Aboriginal in contemporary Australia, and Bruce Pascoe has written both fiction and non-fiction works.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] AustLit's *BlackWords* project provides a comprehensive listing of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Writers and Storytellers.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Living Archive of Aboriginal Languages contains stories written in traditional languages of the Northern Territory.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Australian cinema has a long history, and the ceremonies of Indigenous Australians were among the first subjects to be filmed in Australia – notably a film of Aboriginal dancers in Central Australia, shot by the anthropologist Baldwin Spencer and F.J.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The canon of films related to Indigenous Australians increased from the 1990s, with Nick Parson's film *Dead Heart* (1996) featuring Ernie Dingo and Bryan Brown; Rolf de Heer's *The Tracker* (2002), starring Gary Sweet and David Gulpilil; and Phillip Noyce's *Rabbit-Proof Fence* (2002).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The soundtrack of the 2006 film *Ten Canoes* directed by Rolf de Heer was filmed entirely in dialects of the Yolŋu Matha language group, with the main version featuring subtitles and English narration by David Gulpilil.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The film won the Un Certain Regard Special Jury Prize at the 2006 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] *The Straits*, a 2012 drama series for TV based on an idea by Torres Strait Islander actor Aaron Fa'aoso, was partly filmed in the Torres Strait Islands and starred Fa'aoso and Jimi Bani (from Mabuiag Island), as well as Papua New Guinean actors.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The documentary TV series *Blue Water Empire* (aired 2019), featuring Fa'aoso and Bani, tells the story of Torres Strait Islands from pre-colonial era up to contemporary times.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The films *Sweet Country* (2017), Top End Wedding (2019) and TV series *Cleverman* and *Total Control* (2019), all made by Aboriginal film-makers and featuring Aboriginal themes, were well-received and in some cases won awards.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The third series of the sketch comedy TV series *Black Comedy*, co-written by Nakkiah Lui, Adam Briggs, Steven Oliver and others, and featuring many Indigenous actors, began to air in January 2020.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Though lost to history, many traditional forms of recreation were played and while these varied from tribe to tribe, there were often similarities.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Ball games were quite popular and played by tribes across Australia, as were games based on use of weapons.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] There is extensive documented evidence of traditional football games being played.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Perhaps the most documented is a game popularly played by tribes in western Victorian regions of the Wimmera, Mallee and Millewa by the Djab wurrung, Jardwadjali and Jarijari people.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Known as Marn Grook, it was a type of kick and catch football game played with a ball made of possum hide.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] According to some accounts, it was played as far away as the Yarra Valley by the Wurundjeri people, Gippsland by the Gunai people, and the Riverina in south-western New South Wales.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Some historians claim that Marn Grook had a role in the formation of Australian rules football, and many Aboriginal people, from children in remote communities to professional players at the highest level, the Australian Football League, play the modern game.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Well-known players include Graham Farmer, Gavin Wanganeen, Adam Goodes and Lance Franklin.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Goodes was also the Australian of the Year for 2014.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] A team of Aboriginal cricketers from the Western District of Victoria toured England in 1868, making it the first Australian sports team to travel overseas.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Cricketer and Australian rules football pioneer Tom Wills coached the team in an Aboriginal language he learnt as a child, and Charles Lawrence accompanied them to England.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Johnny Mullagh, the team's star player, was regarded as one of the era's finest batsmen.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Evonne Goolagong became the world number-one ranked female tennis player, with 14 major tennis titles.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Ashleigh Barty, inspired by Goolagong, also reached number-one and won three major singles titles.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Sprinter Cathy Freeman earned gold medals in the Olympics, World Championships, and Commonwealth Games.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Lionel Rose earned a world title in boxing.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Arthur Beetson, Laurie Daley and Gorden Tallis captained Australia in rugby league, while Mark Ella captained Australia in rugby union.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Nathan Jawai and Patty Mills have played in the National Basketball Association.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Sporting teams include the Indigenous All-Stars, Flying Boomerangs and Indigenous Team of the Century in Australian rules football, and the Indigenous All Stars, NSW Koori Knockout and the Murri Rugby League Team in rugby league.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] To this day, the forced removal of children known as the Stolen Generations has had a huge impact on the psyche, health and well-being of Indigenous Australians; it has seriously impacted not only the children removed and their parents, but their descendants as well.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Not only were many of the children abused – psychologically, physically, or sexually – after being removed and while living in group homes or adoptive families, but were also deprived of their culture alongside their families.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] This has resulted in the disruption of oral culture, as parents were unable to communicate their knowledge to their children, and thus much has been lost.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] There are many issues facing Indigenous people in Australia today when compared with the non-Indigenous population, despite some improvements.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Several of these are interrelated, and include health (including shorter life expectancy and higher rates of infant mortality), lower levels of education and employment, inter-generational trauma, high imprisonment rates, substance abuse and lack of political representation.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The federal government's Closing the Gap strategy, created in 2008 and coordinated by the National Indigenous Australians Agency since July 2019, aims to address multiple areas to improve the lives of Indigenous peoples.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Draft targets for 2019 were created by the Council of Australian Governments (COAG) in December 2018.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Social and cultural determinants such as discrimination, lack of education or employment (and therefore income), and cultural disconnection can impact both physical and mental health, and contemporary disadvantage is related to colonisation and its ongoing impact.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The life expectancy of Indigenous Australians is difficult to quantify accurately.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Indigenous deaths are poorly identified, and the official figures for the size of the population at risk include large adjustment factors.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Two estimates of Indigenous life expectancy in 2008 differed by as much as five years.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The ABS introduced a new method in 2009, but problems remained.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] A 2013 study, referring to the national Indigenous reform policy, Closing the Gap, looked at the difficulties in interpreting the extent of the gap because of differing methods of estimating life expectancy between 2007 and 2012.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The 2019 report by the Close the Gap campaign reported that the gap in life expectancy was "widening rather than closing".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Life expectancy for Aboriginals and Torres Strait islanders was 71.6 for men and 75.6 for women as of 2016–2017.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Infant mortality (ages 0–4) was twice as high as for non-Indigenous children in 2014–2016.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Mental health, suicide and self-harm remain major concerns, with the suicide rate being double that of the non-Indigenous population in 2015, and young people experiencing rising rates of mental health difficulties.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] There are high incidences of anxiety, depression, PTSD and suicide amongst the Stolen Generations, with this resulting in unstable parenting and family situations.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Many Indigenous communities suffer from a range of health, social and legal problems associated with substance abuse of both legal and illegal drugs, including but not limited to alcohol abuse, petrol sniffing, the use of illegal drugs such as methamphetamine, cannabis, and smoking tobacco.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Tobacco use has been estimated to be the "greatest contributor (23%) to the gap in the disease burden between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians", with Indigenous people 2.5 times more likely to smoke daily than non-Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Indigenous Australians were 1.6 times more likely to abstain completely from alcohol than non-Indigenous people in 2012–2013.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Foetal alcohol syndrome has been a problem, but the rate of pregnant women drinking had halved between 2008 and 2015 (from 20% to 10%).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Petrol sniffing has been a problem among some remote communities.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The 2018 UQ study also reported that alcohol and cannabis were the drugs causing most concern.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Ice was reported present in 8 of the 25 communities, but nearly all only occasional use.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] There is a significant gap between Indigenous and non-Indigenous people in educational attainment.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] This presents significant issues for employment.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Closing the Gap has focused on improving education for Indigenous people, with some success.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Attainment of Year 12 or equivalent for ages 20–24 has increased from 47.4% in 2006 to 65.3% in 2016.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] This has led to more Indigenous people undertaking higher or vocational education courses.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] According to the *Closing the Gap* report, Indigenous students in higher education award courses more than doubled in number over the decade from 2006 (9,329) to 2017 (19,237).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] However, most of the Closing the Gap targets for education are not on track.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In general, the gaps have improved (such as in NAPLAN results) or not devolved (school attendance rate remaining stable for several years) have not met targets.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Remoteness seems to be a factor; students in isolated or remote communities do not perform or attend as well as students in urban areas.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The *Closing the Gap Report 2019* reported that of the seven targets, only two – early childhood education and Year 12 attainment – had been met.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Only Year 9 numeracy was on track in all states and territories, with variations among them.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Aboriginal Centre for the Performing Arts was established as a training centre by the state and federal governments in 1997.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Compared to the national average, Indigenous people experience high unemployment and poverty rates.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] As of the *2018 Closing the Gap Report*, the Indigenous employment rate had decreased from 48% to 46.6% between 2006 and 2016, while the non-Indigenous employment rate remained steady at around 72% (a 25.4% gap).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The employment rate for Indigenous women, however, increased from 39% to 44.8% in the same period.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Racial Discrimination Act was introduced in 1975, and the Anti-Discrimination Act, in 1977.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Legal action alone cannot prevent all forms of racism, however, these Acts were put into law to place checks on the system.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] A 2016 ABS report on labour force characteristics show low employment rates.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] An analysis of the figures suggested significant barriers to Indigenous people gaining employment, possibly including job location, employer discrimination, and lack of education and others.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Those with a degree had an employment probability of 85% (for males) and 74% (for females) for gaining employment, decreasing along with qualifications, so that those who have completed Year 9 and below have a 43% (male) and 32% (female) probability of gaining employment.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Other factors, unlike education, are not covered by government policy, such as discrimination and unfair treatment.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Employed Indigenous Australians were more likely to experience discrimination than those who are unemployed, and it has been found that the second most common source of unfair treatment (after members of the public) is at work or applying for work.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] There was also a significant lack of consultation with Indigenous peoples on the methods they think best to tackle issues like unemployment.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Indigenous Australians are over-represented in Australia's criminal justice system.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] As of September 2019, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander prisoners represented 28% of the total adult prisoner population, while accounting for 3.3% of the general population.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In May 2018, Indigenous women made up 34% of all women imprisoned in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] It concludes from the data that there is a clear issue occurring not only within Australia's criminal justice system, but within communities as a whole.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Indigenous Australians are also over-represented as victims of crime, in particular, assault.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Indigenous women are highly over-represented in this figure, accounting for a higher proportion of assault victims than the non-Indigenous category.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In 2007, the Northern Territory Government commissioned a Board of Inquiry into the Protection of Aboriginal Children from Sexual Abuse, which produced a report known as the *Little Children are Sacred* report.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] This suggested, based largely on anecdotal evidence, that children in remote Aboriginal communities in NT were suffering from widespread sexual abuse.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Australian Human Rights Commission's *Social Justice Report 2008* said that the 2005–2006 ABS statistics did not appear to support the "allegations of endemic child abuse... that was the rationale for the NTER" ("The Intervention" by the Howard government) that followed.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The rate of family violence in Indigenous Australian communities, especially in the Northern Territory, has been high for many years, and under-reported.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] It has been estimated to be around 34 times greater than the national rate, and, in the worst areas, up to 80 times.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] An AIHW survey covering eight years to 2019, published in December 2021, revealed that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people accounted for 28 per cent of all hospitalisations due to family violence, despite only making up 3.3% of the total population.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In 2021, Australia's government, led by Prime Minister Scott Morrison, announced the creation of a reparations fund for members of the Stolen Generations—Indigenous Australians who were forcibly removed from their homes as children.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] This policy of forced assimilation, which continued into the 1970s, has had lasting impacts on Indigenous communities.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The reparations fund includes one-off payments of 75,000 Australian dollars to victims, as part of a broader initiative to address the serious disadvantages faced by Australia's Indigenous population.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In addition, there's an emerging solidarity between Black and Indigenous communities for finding land justice and reparations.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Initiatives like the Indigenous-led Land Back movement and various Black community organizations are working towards reclaiming land and advocating for financial restitution for civil and human rights violations.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] These movements utilize cooperative structures to advance land justice, emphasizing the importance of communal wealth and regenerative systems that are not extractive of people or the planet.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Under Section 41 of the Australian Constitution, Aboriginal Australians always had the legal right to vote in Australian Commonwealth elections if their State granted them that right.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] This meant that all Aboriginal peoples outside Queensland and Western Australia had a legal right to vote.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The right of Indigenous ex-servicemen to vote was affirmed in 1949 and all Indigenous Australians gained the unqualified right to vote in Federal elections in 1962.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Following the 2010 Australian Federal Election, Ken Wyatt of the Liberal Party won the Western Australian seat of Hasluck, becoming the first Indigenous person elected to the Australian House of Representatives.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] His nephew, Ben Wyatt, was concurrently serving as Shadow Treasurer in the Western Australian Parliament and in 2011 considered a challenge for the Labor Party leadership in that state.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Linda Burney became the second Indigenous person, and the first woman, to serve in the federal House of Representatives.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In March 2013, Adam Giles of the Country Liberal Party (CLP) became Chief Minister of the Northern Territory – the first Indigenous Australian to become head of government in a state or territory of Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Hyacinth Tungutalum, also of the CLP, was the first Indigenous person elected to any Australian (state *or* territory) parliament.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] A Tiwi man from Bathurst Island, he was elected to the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly in October 1974 as the member for Tiwi.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] A number of Indigenous people represent electorates at state and territory level, and South Australia has had an Aboriginal Governor, Sir Douglas Nicholls.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The first Indigenous Australian to serve as a minister in any government was Ernie Bridge, who entered the Western Australian Parliament in 1980.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Carol Martin was the first Aboriginal woman elected to a State parliament in Australia (the Western Australian Legislative Assembly) in 2001, and the first woman minister was Marion Scrymgour, who was appointed to the Northern Territory ministry in 2002 (she became Deputy Chief Minister in 2008).
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Representation in the Northern Territory has been relatively high, reflecting the high proportion of Aboriginal voters.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The 2012 Territory election saw large swings to the conservative CLP in remote Territory electorates, and a total of five Aboriginal CLP candidates won election to the Assembly, along with one Labor candidate, in a chamber of 25 members.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Among those elected for the CLP were high-profile activists Bess Price and Alison Anderson.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Forty people identifying as being of Indigenous Australian ancestry have been members of the ten Australian legislatures.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Of these, 22 have been in the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Northern Territory has an exceptionally high Indigenous proportion (about one third) of its population.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Adam Giles, who was Chief Minister of the Northern Territory from 2013 to 2016, was the first Indigenous head of government in Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In 1974, the year of its creation, the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly was also the first Australian parliament to have an Indigenous member elected to it.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The 2022 election featured the largest number of Indigenous candidates in Australian history, with four running for the Coalition, eleven for Labor, and seventeen for the Greens.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Greens Victorian senate ticket were all Aboriginal.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] As of 2023, Indigenous Australians members of the senate represent 10.5% of the 76 Senate seats, and 1.9% in the House.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The total representation is at 4.8%, far above the national population of 3.3%.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC) was set up as a representative body in 1990 under the Hawke government.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] ICCs operate as whole-of-government centres, housing staff from a number of departments to deliver services to Indigenous Australians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Major political parties in Australia have tried to increase Indigenous representation within their parties.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] One suggestion for achieving this is to introduce seat quotas, as in the Maori electorates in New Zealand.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] His announcement was seen by some as a surprising adoption of the importance of the symbolic aspects of the reconciliation process, and reaction was mixed.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Australian Labor Party initially supported the idea; however Kevin Rudd withdrew this support just before the election, earning a rebuke from activist Noel Pearson.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Government promised to hold a referendum on the constitutional recognition of Indigenous Australians on or before the federal election due for 2013.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The plan was abandoned in September 2012, with Minister Jenny Macklin citing insufficient community awareness for the decision.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In December 2015, the 16-member Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Referendum Council was jointly appointed by the Prime Minister, Malcolm Turnbull, and Leader of the Opposition, Bill Shorten.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] After six months of consultation, the First Nations National Constitutional Convention met over four days from 23 to 26 May 2017, and ratified the *Uluru Statement from the Heart* by a standing ovation from the gathering of 250 Indigenous leaders.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The *Statement* calls for a "First Nations Voice" in the Australian Constitution and a "Makarrata Commission" (*Makarrata* is a Yolngu word "describing a process of conflict resolution, peacemaking and justice").
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In May 2019, Prime Minister Scott Morrison created the position of Minister for Indigenous Australians, a Cabinet portfolio in the Second Morrison Ministry, with Ken Wyatt as the inaugural officebearer.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] On 30 October 2019, Wyatt announced the commencement of a "co-design process" aimed at providing an Indigenous voice to Parliament.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Senior Advisory Group is co-chaired by Professor Tom Calma AO, Chancellor of the University of Canberra, and Professor Dr Marcia Langton, Associate Provost at the University of Melbourne, and comprises a total of 20 leaders and experts from across the country..
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The first meeting of the group was held in Canberra on 13 November 2019.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] About 22% of land in Northern Australia (Kimberley, Top End and Cape York) is now Aboriginal-owned.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In the last decade, nearly 200 native title claims covering 1.3 million km2 of land – approximately 18% of the Australian continent – have been approved.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In 1992, in *Mabo v Queensland*, the High Court of Australia recognised native title in Australia for the first time.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The majority in the High Court rejected the doctrine of *terra nullius*, in favour of the concept of native title.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In 2013, an Indigenous group describing itself as the Murrawarri Republic declared independence from Australia, claiming territory straddling the border between the states of New South Wales and Queensland.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Australia's Attorney General's Department indicated it did not consider the declaration to have any meaning in law.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In 2014, another Indigenous group describing itself as the Sovereign Yidindji Government declared independence from Australia.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] Unlike in other parts of the former British Empire, like the Treaty of Waitangi in New Zealand, no treaty has ever been concluded between Indigenous Australians and an Australian government.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In South Australia, however, following the 2018 state election negotiations have been "paused".
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] In June 2018, the Parliament of Victoria passed a bill to advance the process of establishing a treaty with Aboriginal Victorians.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p03] The Victorian First Peoples' Assembly was elected in November 2019 and sat for the first time on 10 December 2019.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] After the arrival of European settlers in New South Wales, some Indigenous Australians became translators and go-betweens; the best-known was Bennelong, who eventually adopted European dress and customs and travelled to England where he was reportedly presented to King George III.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] Others, such as Pemulwuy, Yagan, and Windradyne, became famous for armed resistance to the European settlers.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] During the twentieth century, as social attitudes shifted and interest in Indigenous culture increased, there were more opportunities for Indigenous Australians to gain recognition.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] Albert Namatjira became a painter, and actors such as David Gulpilil, Ernie Dingo, and Deborah Mailman became well known.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] Bands such as Yothu Yindi, and singers Christine Anu, Jessica Mauboy and Geoffrey Gurrumul Yunupingu, have combined Indigenous musical styles and instruments with pop/rock, gaining appreciation amongst non-Indigenous audiences.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] Polymath David Unaipon is commemorated on the Australian $50 note.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] The voices of Cape York activists Noel Pearson and Jean Little, and academics Marcia Langton and Mick Dodson, today loom large in national debates.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] Some Indigenous people who initially became famous in other spheres – for instance, poet Oodgeroo Noonuccal – have used their celebrity to draw attention to Indigenous issues.
[src:indigenous-australians/indigenous-australians-p04] In health services, Kelvin Kong became the first Indigenous surgeon in 2006 and is an advocate of Indigenous health issues.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:indigenous-australians/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:indigenous-australians/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
